II

Horace no longer finds any pleasure in writing verses, ior love once

more has him in his meshes (1-4). Two years have passed since he .

freed himself from Inachia, who long charmed and tortured him (5-22); now he is ensnared by the fair Lyciscus (23-28). The Pettius to whom

these verses are addressed is otherwise unknown to us. The names ·

Inachia and Lyciscus are borrowed from the Greek. Metre, 80.
